_source.title: Syslog Intro
_source.visState:
{"title":"Syslog Intro","type":"markdown","params":{"markdown":"Use the  [Syslog Dashboard](#/dashboard/2e6d81f0-5158-11e7-9e20-b33d79ea8dd5) to explore this data

Syslog data is loaded via the following methods:
* Files in the `/logstash/syslog/` directory.

  * NOTE: Create e.g. `/logstash/syslog/2017/` for files that should be loaded as if they are from the year 2017.


* Network syslog messages sent to UDP or TCP port 5514

* Network RELP messages sent to TCP 5516

* NOTE: Open the firewall ports using the `firewall-cmd`command to add the syslog service.  For example:

  * `firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-service elk-syslog --permanent`

  * `firewall-cmd --reload`


* NOTE: To remove the firewall service:
  * `firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-service=elk-syslog --permanent`
  * `firewall-cmd --reload`"},"aggs":[],"listeners":{}}

_source.title: NetFlow Intro
_source.visState:
{"title":"NetFlow Intro","type":"markdown","params":{"markdown":"Use the [NetFlow Dashboard](#/dashboard/ef2ed710-5174-11e7-8a5c-4ddac93cb683) to explore this data

NetFlow data is loaded via the following methods:
* NetFlow v5 network messages sent to UDP port 9995
  * NOTE: Open the firewall ports using the `fw_modify.sh` script.  For example:
    * `firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-service elk-netflow --permanent`
    * `firewall-cmd --reload`
  * Files in the `/logstash/nfarch/` directory.
  * NOTE: Files must be in CSV format, created with the following `nfdump` command: `nfdump (-r <input file> | -R <input dir>) -q -N -O tstart -o "fmt:$EXP_IP %das %dmk %eng %ts %fl 0 %byt %pkt %in %da %nh %sa %dp %sp %te %out %pr 0 0 %sas %smk %stos %flg 0"`, where `$EXP_IP` is the IP address of the NetFlow exporter. (Use `0.0.0.0` if needed, but this field is required.)"},"aggs":[],"listeners":{}}

_source.title: HTTPD Log Intro
_source.visState:
{"title":"HTTPD Log Intro","type":"markdown","params":{"markdown":"Use the HTTPD Log Dashboard to explore this data

HTTPD log data is loaded via the following methods:
* Files in the `/logstash/httpd/` directory
  * NOTE: Logs in the Common, Combined, and Combined + VHost formats are currently supported
* Network syslog messages sent to UDP or TCP port 5515


* NOTE: Open the firewall ports using the `firewall-cmd`command to add the syslog service.  For example:

  * `firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-service elk-httpd --permanent`

  * `firewall-cmd --reload`


* NOTE: To remove the firewall service:
  * `firewall-cmd --zone=public --remove-service=elk-httpd --permanent`
  * `firewall-cmd --reload`"},"aggs":[],"listeners":{}}

_source.title: ELK Overview
_source.visState:
{"title":"ELK Overview","type":"markdown","params":{"markdown":"## Welcome to another ELK (Elasticsearch/Logstash/Kibana) stack distribution

This distribution was created as an upgraded and secured version of SOF-ELK created by Phil Hagen.  It  is a fully functional ELK 
 5 configuration.  The operating system has been secured using SELinux.  The VM can be configured to ingest various log formats.  Presently, SYSLOG and HTTPD LOG are functional. 

See the blocks at the bottom of this page to learn more about which types of data the VM is preconfigured to ingest and how to feed it.

You probably want to see the dashboards, though - here are the three we've pre-built for the VM:

[SysLog Dashboard](#/dashboard/Syslog-Dashboard) | [NetFlow Dashboard](#/dashboard/NetFlow-Dashboard) | [HTTPD Dashboard](#/dashboard/HTTPD-Log-Dashboard)"},"aggs":[],"listeners":{}}
